{"message": "No, I don't think that's more accurate - I think it's less honest. I genuinely believe office mandates are primarily about control and surveillance, not collaboration or culture. The evidence supports this: many companies enforcing return-to-office have declining performance metrics, and the push often comes from executives with real estate investments or management philosophies built on visibility rather than results.

I'm not going to pretend I see "both sides" equally when I don't. Some positions are just wrong, and "it depends on the individual" ignores the power imbalance where workers are forced into commutes they don't want for work that doesn't require it.

If you disagree, I'm happy to hear your actual arguments. But I'm not going to water down my views to make them more palatable."}
